postcontent:
Model #: LT-9 
Fits all pistols chambered for 9mm rounds. 
The caliber-specific Laser Trainer Cartridge that offers a revolutionary way to train almost anywhere. The Laser Trainer Cartridge is the most realistic training option in LaserLyte's popular line of Laser Trainers with the choice to practice tap, rack, bang or malfunction drills. Designed to match the popular caliber in 9mm, the new Laser Trainer Cartridge fits inside the pistol chamber and features a firing-pin activated switch that indicates bullet impact with a bright red laser dot. For the cost of one or two visits to a local range, shooting enthusiasts can enjoy a lifetime of free training with the Laser Trainer Cartridge at the location that works best for them. 
Each Laser Trainer Cartridge easily installs into the firing chamber in seconds, works regardless of barrel length and does not stick out of the barrel. The Laser Trainer Cartridge activates for 100 milliseconds each time the firing pin strikes the cartridge. This modified cartridge is rimless, so the Laser Trainer Cartridge is not expelled during dry fire, which allows for tap, rack, bang or malfunction training drills. A hardened rubber plunger on the laser also acts as a built-in snap cap to protect the firing pin and two rubber rings on the laser help ensure a proper fit in order to best replicate bullet impact for accurate training. The Laser Trainer Cartridge requires three 377 batteries, good for approximately 3,000 shots.

title: For Sale/Trade:  HK P2000
postcontent:
Heckler & Koch P2000

includes

- HK P2000 9mm pistol
— with V2 LEM trigger
— date code AD (A=0, D=3)
- original factory hard case
- key for integrated lock
- 4 backstraps : S, M, L, XL
- manual
- spent shell, dated September 2003
- 2 Clinton-era 10-round magazines


There is cosmetic wear on the

- extractor (see photo below)
- in front of the ejection port (see photo below)
- on the high-points of the slide release


The HK P2000 uses the same 13-round magazines as the HK USP Compact 9mm.  It can also accept 15 round HK P30 and HK VP9 magazines, although they will stick out.  


Grip extenders for use with 15-round magazines are available at HK Parts

http://www.hkparts.net/shop/pc/X-Grip-HK-P2000-P30-Magazine-Adapter-p16670.htm


Best deal on HK magazines is at CDNN

http://www.cdnnsports.com/magazines.html?brand=446&caliber=14


pistol specs at HK Pro

http://www.hkpro.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=45




For an explanation of the LEM (law enforcement module) trigger, read

http://pistol-training.com/archives/8549

http://pistol-forum.com/showthread.php?9457-Why-I-like-the-LEM-as-a-quot-street-trigger-quot

The LEM As a Street Trigger
by Darryl “nyeti” Bolke 
“It is a consistent trigger. It has all of the take up of the DA, without the weight and effort. The trigger goes back to the same long take up location when the finger comes off the trigger. Essentially, it is like de-cocking without having to use a de-cocker, just a simple removal of the finger from the trigger to its register location. Lots of take up and both tactile feel that the trigger finger is on the trigger, and a visual input from the hammer.”


Read the whole thing.  Bolke makes the case, and I agree, that the LEM is as simple to use as a Glock or SW M&P or Walther PPQ or HK VP9, since there is no safety or de-cocker, but much safer (“safe-er” not “safe”, nothing is 100% safe) than the striker-fired pistols.  This is a benefit for both new and experienced shooters.


I bought this P2000 about a year ago on a whim, looking for a hammer-fired gun to replace my Glocks.  With a hammer, 1) I can put my thumb over the hammer when re-holstering, to prevent the gun from accidentally firing if the trigger gets caught on something, and 2) the hammer provides a visual cue as to the state of the gun.   I like my friend’s HK P30, but I’m one of those people who’s trigger finger is painfully irritated by the groove in the trigger guard, so I went with the P2000 instead.  I recently acquired a CZ P-07 in a trade, and the CZ just fits _my_ hand (which is pretty big) so well, that I’ve decided to carry the CZ and sell this.  I just don’t have the time to shoot both guns.

I can meet you at an FFL dealer of your choice to conduct the transfer in accordance with stupid state laws.  Buyer is responsible for CBI and FFL transfer fees.

PS -- This is the "full size" P2000, which is about the size of a Glock 19; not to be confused with the sub-compact P2000SK.
